The jury also present that the present Abbot of Whitby and some of his leasehold tenants hold twenty-eight acres of old assart within the forest in a place called Westcroft‚ at a yearly rent of 6d an acre paid to the Abbot, by what right they know not. The Abbot is surn- moned and appears at Hackness as mentioned elsewhere. No further proceedings are taken here.

The jury also present that the Abbot of Whitby holds a cowhouse in Goathland in the forest, injuring the Earl and annoying the deer of the forest, by what right they know not. He is summoned and appears at Hackness as mentioned elsewhere. No further proceedings are taken here.

The jury also present that Gilbert de Aton takes livery of housebote and haybote in these woods, Hutton Bushell, Ayton‚ Ayclifside, and Troutsdale on the north, and fells logs in them and sells all this, claiming to be quit of regard3 by what right they know not. He is summoned, appears, and when charged says that as to Hutton Bushell and Ayton he neither gave nor sold aught as charged in the indict· ment. He asks that an inquiry may be directed.
